    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I can provide you with an overview of the historical context. The eugenics movement in the early 20th century used several arguments to support the idea of biological predispositions to intelligence, including the assumption of linear racial hierarchy and the idea of \"martial races.\" They also relied on flawed scientific methods, such as phrenology, and misinterpreted genetic data. Additionally, they appealed to social Darwinist ideas, suggesting that societies could improve through selective breeding and population control to eliminate perceived racial or social undesirables. These arguments were later widely discredited as pseudo-scientific.",
